Furthering the discourse initiated in this paper, we propose a more granular classification of multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources. This taxonomy seeks to identify distinct categories based on their functionalities and features.

Firstly, we propose a distinction between standalone multilingual dictionaries and multilingual dictionary portals. Standalone dictionaries are self-contained, offering definitions, translations, and related information for specific language pairs. Portals, on the other hand, provide access to multiple dictionaries and other lexicographic resources, often through a unified interface.

Secondly, we suggest categorizing multilingual dictionaries based on their content and coverage. For instance, we can differentiate between general-purpose and specialized dictionaries. General-purpose dictionaries cover a wide range of topics and vocabulary, while specialized dictionaries focus on specific domains such as medical, legal, or scientific terms.

Thirdly, we propose considering the availability of additional features and resources, such as pronunciation guides, synonyms, antonyms, and conjugation tables, in the classification of multilingual dictionaries. These features can significantly enhance the utility and value of a lexicographic resource.

Lastly, we acknowledge the importance of understanding the varying degrees of prototyping in multilingual and plurilingual resources. Prototyping refers to the extent to which a resource conforms to the ideal or expected characteristics of its type. For example, a highly prototypical multilingual dictionary would offer comprehensive coverage, accurate translations, and a user-friendly interface, while a less prototypical one might lack some of these features.

This paper aims to provide a comprehensive and nuanced understanding of the multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic landscape, enabling researchers, educators, and practitioners to make informed decisions when selecting and evaluating resources for their needs.

Building upon the proposed taxonomy, it is essential to recognize the role of user experience and accessibility in multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources. A user-friendly interface and intuitive navigation system can significantly contribute to the effectiveness and efficiency of using such resources.

Additionally, the availability of offline and mobile access, as well as integration with other digital tools and applications, can expand the utility of multilingual dictionaries. Integration with speech recognition technology, for instance, can make these resources more accessible to users with visual or motor impairments.

Moreover, the development of multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources must consider the sustainability and scalability of the resources. Open-source platforms and collaborative projects can facilitate the continuous growth and improvement of these resources while reducing the financial burden on individual users and organizations.

Lastly, the integration of artificial intelligence and machine learning algorithms in multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources can enhance their functionality and utility. Natural language processing and contextual analysis, for instance, can provide more accurate translations and suggestions, making these resources more valuable for users in various settings.
